As Haemonculus said, you're comparing a normal/skilled mage to an unskilled necro.  How many necromancers do you think would actually send their pet in to tank an extra(assuming there was no enchanter or bard present), when they could mez, root-park, or charm(if undead)?  (and I'm not talking about the necros that spend 51-60 exclusively in Skyfire, I mean the ones who know what they're doing).<br>
<br>
And even if they <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> were</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that stupid, why on earth couldn't they harmshield, or FD after the pet died?  If a mage pet dies, what's the mage going to do?<br>
<br>
To the original poster:  My mage is currently level 47, and I've played a friend's 55 necro many times, so I do have experience with both.  Both of those classes are very, very good at soloing(if that's what you want), and either of them can be a large asset to a group if the player behind the controls knows what they're doing.  If you're deciding between necro and mage, look at the spells they get, and decide which one looks more fun to you.  It's kinda like the old druid vs. shaman debats on the Druid's Grove... neither is really <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> better</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->(unless you ask on a class specific board<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ), they're just different.<br>
