<br>
Honestly, the Magician is THE offensive class in the game. 95% of the magician spell book is offense, with a few things like gate, shielding, etc to make us have a slightly better survival rate than a wet paper bag. Even our only buff is an OFFENSIVE buff of a damage shield, being the best damage shield buff in the game (saving a disciplined bard damage shield, that is).<br>
<br>
NOONE, and I mean NOONE can put out damage like a magician until you get to the really high levels against very Magic Resistant mobs, and even then, the epic pet is comparable to many of the melee classes as far as damage output goes. We have the second best nukes in the game (in terms of damage per spell, casting time, and mana efficiency), PLUS we have the pet which serves the twofold purpose of keeping a mob off the magician and increasing his damage output. When I light up a mob it dies and it dies extremely quick.<br>
<br>
If you like to kill mobs, the Magician is your best bet. Take your standard garden variety hill giant. Druids and Necromancers must kite these mobs around by some means, be it root rotting, snare kiting, or fear kiting. This takes time. With the Magician you put a pet on and you mash the nuke key until it is dead.<br>
<br>
ASIDE from all this, the Magician is not all about blasting. Typically in an exp group I nuke once every other fight, if that often. I make my contribution to the group via more indirect methods, I maintain my damage shield on all tanks in the group and I debuff mob resistances making them easier to further debuff, or easier for the enchanter to control. I direct my pet to assist the tank and put out as much damage as many of the tanks in the group. In some cases my pet will out taunt the tank when given opportunity to backstab.<br>
<br>
I serve as a mana stone in a pinch, summoning Modulating Rods for the cleric to give them mana. When the puller has too many mobs but a good lead start I save him and our group by summoning him, wiping his aggro and bringing him back to the group. In the unfortunate event of Corpse Recovery I provide very basic equipment for the group to use to help us get back to our bodies. <br>
<br>
In an AE group I bring alot of power with Sirocco and Scintillation, again second only to the wizard in the amount of damage I can do with an AE blast that does comparable damage to what other blasting classes AE with, with a faster cast time and for less mana. With that same spell of Sirocco I can dish out 1800 points of damage in about 10 seconds against your typical mob.<br>
<br>
And when things do get really messy, I have that reserve of mana that I have not been burning through carelessly. That is when I start to lay on the nukes, and the mob's health drops like a drunk U.S. senator's pants. <br>
<br>
I am a Magician, and I bring a lot to a group. I can solo things that few other classes in the game can kill on their own. I am the offensive class, with a big lump of AI controlled elemental might that will put a serious hurting on what I tell it to.<br>
<br>
The necromancer is a far different creature.<br>
<br>
Alot, and I mean, ALOT of the Necromancer's power comes from two things: Control, and Lifetaps.<br>
<br>
In a fight a good necromancer controls the mobs while Damage Over Time whittles away their hitpoints. Tools such as Fear, Root, Darkness, Screaming Terror, and Feign Death allow the necromancer perhaps the most impressive level of control over the monster AI. This is where a great deal of their power comes from. Soloing a Necromancer can kill a mob without said mob being allowed to hit him or his pet once depending on how his resist rates go, because the mob spends the fight fleeing while the pet and dots chew it up.<br>
In groups the Necromancer is able to control the mobs with Root parking, the ghetto mez spell Screaming Terror, and in some cases is the one who pulls the mobs, being the only class in the game capable of feigning death, invulnerability and rooting, allowing a great deal of ability to single pull mobs, even high level uber mobs.<br>
<br>
Additionally the Necromancer is able to control the vital statistics of the party. Tapping life from enemies give the Necromancer hit points which can be transferred to other party members, or converted into mana which can be transferred to other party members. No other class in the game has a way to directly transfer mana to other players instantaneously.<br>
<br>
Necros are all about control.<br>
<br>
Additionally life taps are arguably one of the most impressive parts of the necromancer arsenal. They restore the necromancer's life while damaging their opponent at the same time, and on top of that have one of the lowest resist rates of any spell in the game.<br>
<br>
Necromancers and Magicians are both very potent classes when it comes to killing things, but the way they go about it is generally very different. The Necromancer kills things through controling the mob, while the Magician kills through utter brute force. <p>Leguin Garamonde<BR>
